{
  "answer": "**The ghazal is chapter 42 (\"Neemcha yaar ne jis waqt baghal mein maara\") of *Diwan-E-Zauq* by Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq.**[^1]\n\nThis ghazal's closing *maqta* (signature couplet), where the poet Zauq humbly concedes he could not attain Mir's distinctive style—while noting how his peers fiercely critiqued (\"struck hard at\") his own attempt at the same *radif* (\"maara\")—reads:\n\n> I could not match the grace of Mir, that master of the art;  \n> Though Zauq, in this ghazal, with force was struck down from the start.[^2]\n\nIts couplet boasting of the sigh-arrow that pierced Saturn's eye (chashm-e-zuhal, the \"evil eye\" of fate's revolving sky) reads:\n\n> The spiteful sky's eye never burst, for all my cries,  \n> But my sigh's arrow struck down Saturn in the skies.[^3]\n\nThe poem also includes the couplet on Qais (Majnun) and Farhad: \"From the hand of great Love, not Qais nor Farhad could flee; One in the desert, one on the mountain, was struck down for all to see.\" (This recurs thematically in the repeated motif of being \"struck down\" (*maara*) by love or rivals.)\n\n[^1]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, [chapter](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/42-neemcha-yaar-ne-jis-waqt-baghal-mein-maara/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, [paragraph](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/42-neemcha-yaar-ne-jis-waqt-baghal-mein-maara/translation/#p-0fdb39).\n\n[^3]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, [paragraph](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/42-neemcha-yaar-ne-jis-waqt-baghal-mein-maara/translation/#p-cc12ee).",
